# Conflict Event Data Analysis and Geospatial Visualization

## Research Question

How does violence against civilians cluster spatially and temporally during the Tigray conflict (November 2020 to November 2022)?

The Tigray conflict began on November 3, 2020, when fighting broke out between Ethiopia's federal government forces and the Tigray People's Liberation Front (TPLF). The conflict escalated through 2021 with multiple armed actors, including Eritrean forces and Amhara regional militias. A Cessation of Hostilities Agreement was signed on November 2, 2022.

## Data Source

UCDP Georeferenced Event Dataset (GED) v25.1
- Source: https://ucdp.uu.se/downloads
- The dataset covers all organized violence globally. We filter to Ethiopia.
- UCDP GED records state-based conflict, non-state conflict, and one-sided violence (violence against civilians).
- Each event is geocoded with latitude/longitude coordinates and includes fatality estimates.
- UCDP v25.1 (October 2025) documented 61 active state-based conflicts, a historic high since 1946.

## Methods

1. Data cleaning and wrangling with pandas
2. Exploratory data analysis: time series, actor breakdowns, fatality distributions
3. Geospatial analysis with geopandas and folium: choropleth maps, point maps, kernel density heatmaps
4. Spatial clustering with DBSCAN (scikit-learn)
5. Temporal comparison across conflict phases

